r-build-yourself-a-loyal-robot-companion" title="Click here to read more about Got a 3D Printer? Build Yourself a Loyal Robot Companion">More&nbsp;&raquo;</a> <br><img width="1" height="1" src="http://gizmodo.feedsportal.com/c/34976/f/647164/s/27c73418/mf.gif" border="0"><br><br><a href="http://da.feedsportal.com/r/151884777935/u/49/f/647164/c/34976/s/27c73418/a2.htm"><img src="http://da.feedsportal.com/r/151884777935/u/49/f/647164/c/34976/s/27c73418/a2.img" border="0"></a><img width="1" height="1" src="http://pi.feedsportal.com/r/151884777935/u/49/f/647164/c/34976/s/27c73418/a2t.img" border="0"><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/gizmodo/full/~4/A9vJ6WMKPuw" height="1" width="1">";s:9:"feed_link";s:19:"http://gizmodo.com/";s:10:"feed_title";s:7:"Gizmodo";}s:32:"530414bd27eaa8e59e2505ce28122d3d";a:7:{s:5:"title";s:51:"Verizon: We sold 6.2M iPhones in the fourth quarter";s:4:"link";s:56:"http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/cnet/tcoc/~3/KSLMQx_Ik20/";s:6:"author";s:11:"Roger Cheng";s:4:"date";i:1358862471;s:7:"content";s:865:"And half of those iPhones were able to tap into the 4G LTE network. Overall, Verizon activated 9.8 million smartphones in the period, with nearly a third new to the service. <a href="http://news.cnet.com/8301-1035_3-57565099-94/verizon-we-sold-6.2m-iphones-in-the-fourth-quarter/?part=rss&amp;subj=news&amp;tag=readMore">[Read more]</a><img width="1" height="1" src="http://cnet.com.feedsportal.com/c/34938/f/645093/s/27c79a6a/mf.gif" border="0"><br><br><a href="http://da.feedsportal.com/r/151884945535/u/49/f/645093/c/34938/s/27c79a6a/a2.htm"><img src="http://da.feedsportal.com/r/151884945535/u/49/f/645093/c/34938/s/27c79a6a/a2.img" border="0"></a><img width="1" height="1" src="http://pi.feedsportal.com/r/151884945535/u/49/f/645093/c/34938/s/27c79a6a/a2t.img" border="0"><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/cnet/tcoc/~4/KSLMQx_Ik20" height="1" width="1">";s:9:"feed_link";s:21:"http://news.cnet.com/";s:10:"feed_title";s:9:"CNET News";}s:32:"fe7909dbc80490d14e419341521cc4c1";a:7:{s:5:"title";s:59:"CyanogenMod 10.1 Milestone 1 hits Nexus and Samsung devices";s:4:"link";s:62:"http://www.engadget.com/2013/01/22/cyanogenmod-10-1-milestone/";s:6:"author";s:10:"Jon Fingas";s:4:"date";i:1358862300;s:7:"content";s:1981:"<p> <a href="http://www.engadget.com/2013/01/22/cyanogenmod-10-1-milestone/"><img alt="CyanogenMod 101 Milestone 1 hits Nexus and Samsung devices" data-src-height="417" data-src-width="568" src="http://www.blogcdn.com/www.engadget.com/media/2013/01/cyanogenmod-cid-mascot.jpg"></a></p><p> Despite all the nightly builds of <a href="http://www.engadget.com/tag/cyanogenmod10.1">CyanogenMod 10.1</a>, there hasn't been much of anything definitive to hang our hats on. There's at last some sense of reliability now that Milestone 1 versions have hit the servers. Most Nexus devices, as well as swaths of Samsung's Galaxy S and <a href="http://www.engadget.com/tag/GalaxyTab2,review/">Galaxy Tab 2</a> ranges, can get the unofficial Android 4.2 build for themselves. The M1 code is deemed "mostly stable" and good enough for daily use, although that's relative -- it's not yet to the level of a <a href="http://www.engadget.com/2012/11/13/stable-cyanogenmod-10-builds-arrive/">fully stable</a> build, let alone factory firmware. If you only needed fewer risks than before, though, the downloads and details await at the source links.<br><br> [Thanks, Rashid]</p><p>Filed under: <a href="http://www.engadget.com/category/cellphones/" rel="tag">Cellphones</a>, <a href="http://www.engadget.com/category/mobile/" rel="tag">Mobile</a>, <a href="http://www.engadget.com/category/samsung/" rel="tag">Samsung</a>, <a href="http://www.engadget.com/category/google/" rel="tag">Google</a></p><p><strong><a href="http://www.engadget.com/2013/01/22/cyanogenmod-10-1-milestone/#comments">Comments</a></strong></p><p><strong>Via:</strong> <a href="http://donandroid.com/cm10-1-m1-for-galaxy-s3-nexus-4-7-10-captivate-tab-2-724" target="_blank">DonAndroid</a><!--//--></p><p><strong>Source:</strong> <a href="http://get.cm/?type=snapshot" target="_blank">CyanogenMod (1)</a><!--//-->, <a href="http://www.cyanogenmod.org/blog/cm-10-1-m-series-builds-have-arrived" target="_blank">(2)</a><!--//--></p>";s:9:"feed_link";s:24:"http://www.engadget.com/";s:10:"feed_title";s:8:"Engadget";}s:32:"eb3e2a7c8820faf4ae9f1187f08af32e";a:7:{s:5:"title";s:60:"iPhone wins 51 percent of U.S. smartphone sales, says report";s:4:"link";s:56:"http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/cnet/tcoc/~3/SyWueOqh_1Y/";s:6:"author";s:13:"Lance Whitney";s:4:"date";i:1358861836;s:7:"content";s:848:"Apple snared more than 50 percent of U.S. smartphone sales last quarter, says Kantar, though Android remained dominant across Europe and the world. <a href="http://news.cnet.com/8301-13579_3-57565106-37/iphone-wins-51-percent-of-u.s-smartphone-sales-says-report/?part=rss&amp;subj=news&amp;tag=readMore">[Read more]</a><img width="1" height="1" src="http://cnet.com.feedsportal.com/c/34938/f/645093/s/27c71dc9/mf.gif" border="0"><br><br><a href="http://da.feedsportal.com/r/151884691851/u/49/f/645093/c/34938/s/27c71dc9/a2.htm"><img src="http://da.feedsportal.com/r/151884691851/u/49/f/645093/c/34938/s/27c71dc9/a2.img" border="0"></a><img width="1" height="1" src="http://pi.feedsportal.com/r/151884691851/u/49/f/645093/c/34938/s/27c71dc9/a2t.img" border="0"><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/cnet/tcoc/~4/SyWueOqh_1Y" height="1" width="1">";s:9:"feed_link";s:21:"http://news.cnet.com/";s:10:"feed_title";s:9:"CNET News";}s:32:"d7ecac3fe5aa120a52457d29f27a0f14";a:7:{s:5:"title";s:40:"Mozilla devs working on Firefox for OUYA";s:4:"link";s:60:"http://www.engadget.com/2013/01/22/mozilla-firefox-for-ouya/";s:6:"author";s:10:"Nicole Lee";s:4:"date";i:1358860440;s:7:"content";s:2257:"<p> <a href="http://www.engadget.com/2013/01/22/mozilla-firefox-for-ouya/"><img alt="DNP Mozilla devs working to get Firefox on the OUYA" data-src-height="465" data-src-width="620" src="http://www.blogcdn.com/www.engadget.com/media/2013/01/firefoxouya.jpg"></a></p><p> Sure the <a href="http://engadget.com/tag/ouya">OUYA</a> may have captured the imagination of <a href="http://www.engadget.com/2013/01/07/ouya-and-kill-screen-announce-create-game-jam/">indie game developers</a> everywhere, but open-source fans will be glad to know it's sparked the interest of Mozilla's <a href="http://engadget.com/tag/firefox">Firefox</a> team as well. According to an <em>OUYAForum</em> post by administrator Ed Krassenstein, a Mozilla developer had sent him a note detailing the process of bringing the popular browser to the <a href="http://www.engadget.com/2012/08/09/ouyas-kickstarter-funding-is-complete-over-8-5-million-raised/">Kickstarter-funded gaming console</a>. The team apparently managed to get it running after some preliminary patches, but it still has a ways to go -- WebGL, Canvas and relevant API support are still lacking. The dev in question has since been identified as mobile platform engineer Chris Lord, who tweeted the revealing picture above along with the note that it's "kinda unusable" for now. Still, they do have around <a href="http://www.engadget.com/2012/08/09/ouya-console-pre-order/">three months before the console ships</a>, which could be enough for them to perfect an OUYA version of the foxy browser just in time for launch day.</p><p> [Image credit: <a href="https://twitter.com/cwiiis/status/293390930009026560/photo/1">Chris Lord</a>, Twitter]</p><p>Filed under: <a href="http://www.engadget.com/category/gaming/" rel="tag">Gaming</a></p><p><strong><a href="http://www.engadget.com/2013/01/22/mozilla-firefox-for-ouya/#comments">Comments</a></strong></p><p><strong>Via:</strong> <a target="_blank" href="http://techcrunch.com/2013/01/21/mozilla-devs-are-working-to-optimize-firefox-for-the-ouya-android-game-console/">TechCrunch</a><!--//--></p><p><strong>Source:</strong> <a target="_blank" href="http://ouyaforum.com/showthread.php?1122-Mozilla-is-working-to-bring-Firefox-to-OUYA!&amp;p=6901">OUYAforum</a><!--//--></p>";s:9:"feed_link";s:24:"http://www.engadget.com/";s:10:"feed_title";s:8:"Engadget";}s:32:"142281e0a3cff7a4885b1c8fccdfe20c";a:7:{s:5:"title";s:59:"Verizon's FiOS TV Subscriber Growth Slows in Fourth Quarter";s:4:"link";s:66:"http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/thr/news/~3/4x9ZQ9gkz7k/story01.htm";s:6:"author";s:12:"Georg Szalai";s:4:"date";i:1358859217;s:7:"content";s:2568:"<img src="http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/sites/default/files/2011/10/37207verizonlogoprhr_a_l.jpg"><br>The telecom giant signed up 134,000 new pay TV subscribers, down from 194,000 in the year-ago period.<p><a href="http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/fios-tv-fourth-quarter-subscribers-414237" target="_blank">read more</a></p><img width="1" height="1" src="http://rss.feedsportal.com/c/34793/f/641578/s/27c70300/mf.gif" border="0"><div><table border="0"><tr><td valign="middle"><a href="http://share.feedsportal.com/viral/sendEmail.cfm?lang=en&amp;title=Verizon%27s+FiOS+TV+Subscriber+Growth+Slows+in+Fourth+Quarter&amp;link=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.hollywoodreporter.com%2Fnews%2Ffios-tv-fourth-quarter-subscribers-414237" target="_blank"><img src="http://res3.feedsportal.com/images/emailthis2.gif" border="0"></a></td><td valign="middle"><a href="http://res.feedsportal.com/viral/bookmark.cfm?title=Verizon%27s+FiOS+TV+Subscriber+Growth+Slows+in+Fourth+Quarter&amp;link=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.hollywoodreporter.com%2Fnews%2Ffios-tv-fourth-quarter-subscribers-414237" target="_blank"><img src="http://res3.feedsportal.com/images/bookmark.gif" border="0"></a></td></tr></table></div><div>
