</div><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/thr/news/~4/MjAtIOElhvw" height="1" width="1">";s:9:"feed_link";s:33:"http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/";s:10:"feed_title";s:18:"Hollywood Reporter";}s:32:"150f6f79522f09867121a0e06647080a";a:7:{s:5:"title";s:43:"Intel Launches Budget Ivy Bridge Processors";s:4:"link";s:98:"http://feeds.gawker.com/~r/gizmodo/full/~3/tVz6xyBE3bU/intel-launches-budget-ivy-bridge-processors";s:6:"author";s:15:"Jamie Condliffe";s:4:"date";i:1358849517;s:7:"content";s:1847:"<div> <!-- div style="background-color: #B3B3B3; width: 190px; padding: 1px;"><a title="Click here to read Intel Launches Budget Ivy Bridge Processors" href="http://gizmodo.com/guts/" style="background-color:#888888; color:#FFFFFF; font-size:12px;text-align:right; display:block; height:14px; padding:1px 2px; text-decoration:none; text-transform:uppercase; width:156px;"><span style="color: white;" class="hash">#</span><span style="color: white;">guts</span></a></div --> <div><a title="Click here to read Intel Launches Budget Ivy Bridge Processors" href="http://gizmodo.com/5977900/intel-launches-budget-ivy-bridge-processors"> <img height="360" width="640" title="Click here to read Intel Launches Budget Ivy Bridge Processors" alt="Click here to read Intel Launches Budget Ivy Bridge Processors" src="http://img.gawkerassets.com/img/18c9l8q1mdzcsjpg/xlarge.jpg"></a></div> </div> Now that Intel has its efficient and expensive Ivy Bridge microarchitecture in tablets and computers everywhere, it's decided to launch a budget-friendly line of processors which use the same 22nm manufacturing process. <a href="http://gizmodo.com/5977900/intel-launches-budget-ivy-bridge-processors" title="Click here to read more about Intel Launches Budget Ivy Bridge Processors">More&nbsp;&raquo;</a> <br><img width="1" height="1" src="http://gizmodo.feedsportal.com/c/34976/f/647164/s/27c54558/mf.gif" border="0"><br><br><a href="http://da.feedsportal.com/r/151884768889/u/49/f/647164/c/34976/s/27c54558/kg/342/a2.htm"><img src="http://da.feedsportal.com/r/151884768889/u/49/f/647164/c/34976/s/27c54558/kg/342/a2.img" border="0"></a><img width="1" height="1" src="http://pi.feedsportal.com/r/151884768889/u/49/f/647164/c/34976/s/27c54558/kg/342/a2t.img" border="0"><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/gizmodo/full/~4/tVz6xyBE3bU" height="1" width="1">";s:9:"feed_link";s:19:"http://gizmodo.com/";s:10:"feed_title";s:7:"Gizmodo";}s:32:"ca54a82d1315978e7b6ac70f12ea542e";a:7:{s:5:"title";s:76:"Huawei unveils Ascend G615: 4.5-inch 720p screen, 1.4GHz quad-core processor";s:4:"link";s:62:"http://www.engadget.com/2013/01/22/huawei-ascend-g615-germany/";s:6:"author";s:13:"Alexis Santos";s:4:"date";i:1358848860;s:7:"content";s:2220:"<p> <a href="http://www.engadget.com/2013/01/22/huawei-ascend-g615-germany/"><img alt="Huawei unveils Ascend G615: 4.5-inch 720p screen, 1.4 GHz quad-core processor" data-src-height="340" data-src-width="620" src="http://www.blogcdn.com/www.engadget.com/media/2013/01/ascend-g615.jpg"></a></p><p> <a href="http://www.engadget.com/tag/Huawei/">Huawei's</a> just unveiled the Ascend G 615 (not to be confused with the <a href="http://www.engadget.com/2013/01/15/huawei-g520-smartphone/">G 520</a>) in Germany, and it's packing a 4.5-inch 720p IPS display and 1.4GHz quad-core processor for 299 euros. In addition to the silicon, 8GB of built-in storage, 1GB of RAM and a microSD slot hide behind the 330 ppi display. As for optics, the phone carries a 1.3-megapixel front-facing cam and an 8-megapixel shooter accompanied by a dual-LED flash, and records 1080p footage. In terms of connectivity, the device features support for WiFi, Bluetooth and pulling down 21Mbps over HSDPA. Next month, the G 615 will be served up in Germany with Ice Cream Sandwich onboard, but Huawei says the hardware will be updated to Jelly Bean at some point in March. There's no word on a US release, but it's expected to hit the road for a few international markets in short order. If Huawei's latest offering strikes your fancy and you call Deutschland home, hit the source links for more details.</p><p>Filed under: <a href="http://www.engadget.com/category/cellphones/" rel="tag">Cellphones</a>, <a href="http://www.engadget.com/category/mobile/" rel="tag">Mobile</a></p><p><strong><a href="http://www.engadget.com/2013/01/22/huawei-ascend-g615-germany/#comments">Comments</a></strong></p><p><strong>Via:</strong> <a target="_blank" href="http://androidcommunity.com/huawei-ascend-g615-announced-with-quad-core-and-4-5-inch-hd-display-20130121/">Android Community</a><!--//--></p><p><strong>Source:</strong> <a target="_blank" href="http://www.ascendg615.huaweidevices.de/">Huawei</a><!--//-->, <a target="_blank" href="http://translate.google.com/translate?sl=auto&amp;tl=en&amp;js=n&amp;prev=_t&amp;hl=en&amp;ie=UTF-8&amp;eotf=1&amp;u=http%3A%2F%2Fbestboyz.de%2Fascend-g615%2F%3Fystfuv&amp;act=url">BestBoyZ (translated)</a><!--//--></p>";s:9:"feed_link";s:24:"http://www.engadget.com/";s:10:"feed_title";s:8:"Engadget";}s:32:"1c1ef56bf4f949a2e40316e3302d9d78";a:7:{s:5:"title";s:56:"European Union Report Proposes Stricter Media Regulation";s:4:"link";s:66:"http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/thr/news/~3/9eIJncwCdr8/story01.htm";s:6:"author";s:12:"Georg Szalai";s:4:"date";i:1358846940;s:7:"content";s:2607:"<img src="http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/sites/default/files/2013/01/neelie_kroes_1.jpeg"><br>It proposes EU-wide rules in such areas as libel laws and media councils with the right to impose fines and order apologies by media outlets.<p><a href="http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/european-union-stricter-media-regulation-414230" target="_blank">read more</a></p><img width="1" height="1" src="http://rss.feedsportal.com/c/34793/f/641578/s/27c4cba9/mf.gif" border="0"><div><table border="0"><tr><td valign="middle"><a href="http://share.feedsportal.com/viral/sendEmail.cfm?lang=en&amp;title=European+Union+Report+Proposes+Stricter+Media+Regulation&amp;link=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.