div> You're not going to find anymore gun-related deals on Groupon, at least temporarily. The company says the entire fire arms <a href="http://www.dailyfinance.com/2013/01/20/gun-shop-groupon-boycott-michael-cargill/">category is under review</a>: <a href="http://gizmodo.com/5977727/groupon-is-done-with-all-gun-deals" title="Click here to read more about Groupon Is Done With All Gun Deals">More&nbsp;&raquo;</a> <br><img width="1" height="1" src="http://gizmodo.feedsportal.com/c/34976/f/647164/s/27c0ed35/mf.gif" border="0"><br><br><a href="http://da.feedsportal.com/r/151884749978/u/49/f/647164/c/34976/s/27c0ed35/a2.htm"><img src="http://da.feedsportal.com/r/151884749978/u/49/f/647164/c/34976/s/27c0ed35/a2.img" border="0"></a><img width="1" height="1" src="http://pi.feedsportal.com/r/151884749978/u/49/f/647164/c/34976/s/27c0ed35/a2t.img" border="0"><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/gizmodo/full/~4/vHx7fCqE0Uk" height="1" width="1">";s:9:"feed_link";s:19:"http://gizmodo.com/";s:10:"feed_title";s:7:"Gizmodo";}s:32:"97670c0ebc2c63e5dc016ce5f21198fb";a:7:{s:5:"title";s:51:"Pow! Bam! Original Batmobile sells for $4.6 million";s:4:"link";s:56:"http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/cnet/tcoc/~3/9zR1_UHY0wg/";s:6:"author";s:13:"Amanda Kooser";s:4:"date";i:1358803704;s:7:"content";s:804:"The Caped Crusader's super-funky ride from 1966 broke auction records and is now in the hands of a new owner. <a href="http://news.cnet.com/8301-17938_105-57565026-1/pow-bam-original-batmobile-sells-for-%244.6-million/?part=rss&amp;subj=news&amp;tag=readMore">[Read more]</a><img width="1" height="1" src="http://cnet.com.feedsportal.com/c/34938/f/645093/s/27c0ec81/mf.gif" border="0"><br><br><a href="http://da.feedsportal.com/r/151884749898/u/49/f/645093/c/34938/s/27c0ec81/a2.htm"><img src="http://da.feedsportal.com/r/151884749898/u/49/f/645093/c/34938/s/27c0ec81/a2.img" border="0"></a><img width="1" height="1" src="http://pi.feedsportal.com/r/151884749898/u/49/f/645093/c/34938/s/27c0ec81/a2t.img" border="0"><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/cnet/tcoc/~4/9zR1_UHY0wg" height="1" width="1">";s:9:"feed_link";s:21:"http://news.cnet.com/";s:10:"feed_title";s:9:"CNET News";}s:32:"3f68c872fb08ecff0adc5cdb5f65e29f";a:7:{s:5:"title";s:74:"Cotton-polymer material absorbs or repels moisture depending how hot it is";s:4:"link";s:92:"http://www.engadget.com/2013/01/21/cotton-polymer-absorbs-repels-water-based-on-temperature/";s:6:"author";s:14:"Michael Gorman";s:4:"date";i:1358803260;s:7:"content";s:2612:"<p> <a href="http://www.engadget.com/2013/01/21/cotton-polymer-absorbs-repels-water-based-on-temperature/"><img alt="Cottonpolymer material absorbs or repels moisture depending how hot it is" data-src-height="167" data-src-width="260" src="http://www.blogcdn.com/www.engadget.com/media/2013/01/cottonmagic-1358797001.jpg"></a>Aside from the sweltering daytime heat and the freezing night-time temperatures, the biggest problem for folks living in desert regions is finding sources of water. Researchers from <a href="http://www.engadget.com/tag/eindhovenuniversityoftechnology/">Eindhoven University of Technology</a> and Hong Kong Polytechnic have leveraged those temperature swings to help solve the arid region hydration conundrum with a cotton material that absorbs water straight from the surrounding air. Of course, it's not your run-of-the-mill fabric woven from fluffy white stuff. This cloth is coated in a special polymer, called PNIPAAm, that's hydrophilic (read: super absorbent) at temperatures 34&deg;C and below, but becomes hydrophobic (read: repels water) when it gets any hotter. </p><p> In absorption mode, the cloth can hold 340 percent of its own weight -- compared to just 18 percent without the polymer's aid -- and when it warms up, it releases the collected moisture as clean and pure potable water. So, it can help hydrate both plants <em>and</em> people in desert regions around the world. The boffins who created the stuff claim it's reusable and can be used on locally-sourced cotton fabrics for a minimal, 12 percent cost increase given current manufacturing conditions. Not impressed? Well, the magical moisture-absorbing material may get even better, as the plan is to increase the amount of water the material can hold and lower the temperature threshold for its release. </p><p>Filed under: <a href="http://www.engadget.com/category/wearables/" rel="tag">Wearables</a>, <a href="http://www.engadget.com/category/science/" rel="tag">Science</a>, <a href="http://www.engadget.com/category/alt/" rel="tag">Alt</a></p><p><strong><a href="http://www.engadget.com/2013/01/21/cotton-polymer-absorbs-repels-water-based-on-temperature/#comments">Comments</a></strong></p><p><strong>Via:</strong> <a target="_blank" href="http://www.extremetech.com/extreme/146276-cheap-polymer-coated-cotton-automagically-captures-water-from-desert-air">Extreme Tech</a><!--//--></p><p><strong>Source:</strong> <a target="_blank" href="http://www.tue.nl/en/university/news-and-press/news/cotton-with-special-coating-collects-water-from-fogs-in-desert/">Eindhoven University of Technology</a><!--//--></p>";s:9:"feed_link";s:24:"http://www.engadget.com/";s:10:"feed_title";s:8:"Engadget";}s:32:"94e697a58400047beb287883f37006dc";a:7:{s:5:"title";s:65:"Awesome 5-foot Lego Nintendo Gamepad Works Just Like the Real One";s:4:"link";s:120:"http://feeds.gawker.com/~r/gizmodo/full/~3/ZARewjweIpE/awesome-5+foot-lego-nintendo-gamepad-works-just-like-the-real-one";s:6:"author";s:10:"Jesus Diaz";s:4:"date";i:1358803200;s:7:"content";s:1955:"<div> <!-- div style="background-color: #B3B3B3; width: 190px; padding: 1px;"><a title="Click here to read Awesome 5-foot Lego Nintendo Gamepad Works Just Like the Real One" href="http://gizmodo.com/lego/" style="background-color:#888888; color:#FFFFFF; font-size:12px;text-align:right; display:block; height:14px; padding:1px 2px; text-decoration:none; text-transform:uppercase; width:156px;"><span style="color: white;" class="hash">#</spa